edo 29 2 6 P. 81 29 4 a\nValdez, Doroteo, 2901 South Flores 33 1 4 p' 96 29 29 \u201c9\nValdez, Higinio, 413 Monterey 21 2 6 X. 46 21 21 21\nVasquez, Juan G\u201e 702 Dolorosa 24 2 6 P, 79 24 6 6\nWoodruff, T. W\u201e 115 East Theo avenue...63 1 4 X. 46 37 14 74\nYtuarte, Candelario, 1531 El Paso 49 2 5 P. 321 49 14 74\nsmoker will be held for the mem\nber*.\nit is probable that the present of\nficers will be re-elected. The society is\nIN 1898\nALL DRUGGISTS\nSAN ANTONIO LIGHT AND GAZETTE\nin a prosperous condition, which is\ndue to the energy and efficiency of\nits officers. The Bexar County Medi\ncal association is the best organised\nin the state. In the entire fifty mak\ning up the State Medical association\nthere is not one which can compare\nwith this society for initiative and\nprogressiveness.\nUSES WHIP UPON HUSBAND\nWhen Ho Flees the Wife Obtains a\nWarrant for Desertion.\nLancaster, Pa., Dec. 17.\u2014That a\nsensational horsewhipping of a hus\nband by his infuriated wife took place\nin the lobby of the Woodworth build\ning in this city last night became\nknown today when Mrs. Elizabeth A.\nDegeirs of New York swore out a\ncomplaint against her husband for\ndesertion.\nMrs. Degeirs came here yesterday\nin search of her husband. R. Francis\nDegeirs. a bond salesman. On catch\ning sight of him she drew a whip\nfrom under her coat and belabored\nhim unmercifully. Degeirs finally es\ncaped and dashed for a train which\nwas just pulling out from the depot.\nOCTOPUS SEIZES WOMAN\nArizona-Tourist In California Catches\nDevilfish. Is Caught, and\nFaints.\nLong Beach. Cal., Dec. Yt. \u2014Mrs.\nJessie McDonald of Tucson, Ariz., was\nseized by an octopus, which she land\ned while fishing at the pier yester\nday.\nThe fish, which measured two feet\nacross, immediately wound a tentacle\naround the woman's ankle.\nMrs. McDonald fainted and so firm\nwas the grip of the young sea monster\nthat efforts of spectators to remove it\nwere unsuccessful until a fisherman\napplied a knife to its feeler.\nTHE WORLD SEES YOU\nare aging if gray hairs begin to ap\npear. Wells' Hair Balsam so gradual\nly and perfectly restores gray hairs to\noriginal color that no one would sus\npect you of using anything. 60c and\nJ 1.00 at druggists E. S. Well*, chem\nist, Jersey City, N. J-\n|||y Taste is the\nBest Syrup Test\nBMB You can\u2019t go wrong if you trust\nyour palate. Have you tasted HI IIW'\nVeIva 1\nI Breakfast Syrup 1\nTaste it. You\u2019ll recognize the real flavor of unadulterated sugar cane\nW juice even if you never tasted it before. Instinct will say right off, B\n\u201cThat\u2019s it. That\u2019s the real thing.\u201d After you\u2019ve\n7 tasted Velva taste any other kind. You can\nMany Hombres Are Put to Work\non Street Gang and Work is Humming\n\"I witnessed a sight this morning,\nthat 1 haven't seen for many years.\nSome eighteen or twenty years ago,\nMexicans were corralled upon the\nnear approach of an election ahd put\nto worn by the city administration on\nthe streets. This was before the ad\nvent ot the poll tax system and be\nfore the Terrell election law was\nknown. Today on South Santa Rosa\navenue and Buena Vista street, 1 saw\na hundred or more Mexicans shoveling\nup the mud on the streets and carting\nit to some other point. In view of the\nfact that an election is not many days\noft, the incident brought vividly to\nmind the stirring scenes that charac\nterized a political campaign in San\nAntonio years ago, when, with Mexi\ncans, an administration would defeat\nall other opposition.\"\nThus spoke an old resident of San\nAntonio this morning. An investiga\ntion proved that what he said was\ntrue. Along South Santa Rosa ave\nnue and along Buena Vista street, a\nhundred or more Mexicans armed\nwith shovels were found scooping up\nthe slush and dumping it into wagons\nto be carted to some other point in the\ncity. They were in the employ of the\ncity administration, all doubtless arm\ned with a poll tax and each represent\ning a vote against the commission\ngovernment charter.\n\"Yes,'' said the resident, \u201cif the,\ncommission charter should happen to\nbe not ratified, it will be because the 1\ncity has several thousand Mexicans in\nline to vote against it.\u201d\nThe scene on Santa Rosa avenue\nthis morning was the source of much\ncom...ent among those who passed by\nin street cars or chanced to pass\nthrough the neighborhood. For years\nthis particular thoroughfare has re- i\ncelved little or no attention from the\ncity. The rough driveway was \\per-\nmitted to remain in the same cundt- i\ntion for months after months, but now\nthat an election is scheduled in which\na movement threatens to sound the\ndeath knell, politically, to the present j\noffice-holders, property owners were I\ntreated to a sudden change of heart\nand a decision that the thoroughfare\nwas in need of attention.\nEarly yesterday morning when the\ngreat number of Mexicans appeared\non the scene, those in the vicinity were.\ngiven a fright, some, it is said, being\nprone to believe that General Madero\nwas marching through the city on his\nway to Mexico and that the army I\nmight begin active operations and\nopen fire before the border was reach\ned. But when the men were later\narmed with shovels, those who have 1\nresided here for some time, under\nstood that it was the old method of\nreinforcing the voting strength of the\ncity, that the administration might\nthwart any effort on the part of citi\nzens to improve upon municipal oper\nations.\nWhile not official, it is understood\nthat property owners will, during the\ntime intervening between now and the\nelection in February, be treated to\nstreet improvements in the way of dirt\nscraping and gutter cleaning and in\nsome instances thoroughfares might\neven be given a new cover of ma\ncadam, something they have not en\njoyed in several years.\nRtcbe Undertaking co., auto ambui\nance service. 221 E. Com. Phone 341\nCREW IS RESCUED.\nAssociated Press.\nPensacola, Fla., Dec. 16.\u2014With,the\ncrew of the schooner Stella L, aboard,\nthe tug E. E. Simpson has arrived\nfrom the gulf, having picked the men\nup in an almost starving condition,\neight miles off the Pensacola light\nhouse, where they had remained for\nabout three days, their supply of pro\nvisions becoming exhausted after the\nfirst day.\nThe Stella L is a small vessel from\nPerdido bay and as it usually re\nquired only twenty-four hours to\nmake the run, no supplies were\naboard. In coming out of Perdido\nbay Monday, the schooner was caught\nin a squall and disabled.\nTo cure scrofula, salt rheum, dyspepsia,\ncatarrh and rheumatism, take Hood\u2019s Sarsa\nparilla.\nCX ZX\nwhich fat?\u201d\n\u201cr |t| Any product which contains hog fat is subject\nto the taint or possibility of disease germs. Lard is\nma^e f rom hog fat\u2014it may be pure and it may not.\nrAt any rate, it is at best indigestible, and will raise\ng havoc with any but the hardiest stomach.\nCottolene is a vegetable product, which is far\nsuperior to lard for all shortening and frying pur-\nnoses. It is an absolutely pure and healthful _ _\nlb Cl 11 pucv H\nfat made from cotton oil.\nCottolene is a product of nature and is bound to be\nwholesome. It is the one dependable, healthful product\nfor frying and shortening, and is carefully inspected and\nmade to conform with all pure\nfood laws.\nMade onlr bv\nTHE N. K. FAIRBANK COMPANY\nThe Swine or\nthe Flower?\ntell the difference right away even if you B\ndon\u2019t know what makes the difference. B\nThere are a great many part-cane syrups\nP art corn husks, part cane; part this and that. B\nVelva is the pure juice of the finest sugar\ncanc rows We crush it out and\nc l it, and can it in individual cans.\nh as that \u201cBefore the War\u201d taste.\nYour can is waiting for you at\nyour erocer,s\nrE N 1 c Ki-a fo RD. Lt\u00bb\nBARONESS NOW HAS\nHIGHEST COURT RANK\nAssociated Preu.\nWashington, Dec. 16. Baroness\nHengehnuller. wife of the ambassador\nfrom Austria-Hungary to the United\nStates, has been designated by Emper\nor Francis Joseph as the imperial and\nroyal lady of the palace, according to\na cablegram received at the embassy\nhere. This gives her the highest rank\nand privileges of the court. Baroness\nHengelmuller Is now visiting in New\nYork.\nDr. C. F. Dunlap, dentist. Moore\nBuilding.\nCOUNTERFEIT UNION LABEL.\nAssociated Press.\nNew York, Dec. 16. \u2014A number of\nmanufacturers of this city have coun\nterfeited the union label, according\nto a statement i..ade to District At\ntorney Whiteman. by Samuel Gom\npers. president of the American Fed\neration of Labor. Mr. Gompers re\nquested that the matter be taken be\nfore the grand jury and he supplied a\nlist of accused firms.\nDECEMBER 16, 1910.\nIN HIS STEPS.\nNew Big Game Party Will Go to\nAfrica to Kill What Roose\nvelt Deft.\nAssociated Press,\nLexington. Ky.. Dec. 16. \u2014Dr. Mar\nius Johnston, son of Adjutant Gen\neral P. P Johnston, is planning to\nsail with Paul J. Rainey, the million\naire sportsman of Cleveland, Ohio,\nfrom New York in February, for an\nextended hunting trip in the heart of\nEc-st Africa. In a general way the\nhunt will follow the route covered by\nCol. Roosevelt.\nDr. Johnston accompanied Harry\nWhi y and Mr. Rainey on their Arc\ntic trip last summer. At present he is\nin Georgia.\nTYPHOID ON WANE.\nAssociated Press.\nWashington. Dec. 16.\u2014The typhoid\nepidemic at Annapolis, in the opinion\nof the medical officials of the navy,\nis on the wane. Among thq. thirty\npatients there are now only one or two\nserious cases, and barring unforseen\ndevelopments. Surgeon General Stokes\nis confident that all will recover.","height":"26660","width":"20164"}}
